  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Accessing Health Rights in Ghana</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In sexual and reproductive health matters, many women in Ghana are excluded from decision-making, even in relation to their own welfare. They often do not make decisions about contraception, how many children they will have, or whether or not they deliver their babies with a skilled health provider who could help them in the event of complications during childbirth. They are the primary caregivers for children, but often do not control household income. This can prevent them from seeking health care for themselves and their children when ill. This project will promote Ghana&#x2019;s National Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS), which gives people access to basic health care for an annual registration fee and covers most illnesses. A recent evaluation found better health outcomes for women registered in the NHIS when compared against those that were not enrolled. However, in the area where the project is taking place, registration in this scheme is low. This project will combine ongoing work on women&#x2019;s rights specifically in the areas of sexual and reproductive health with activities to increase the percentage of people enrolled in the NHIS, particularly the most marginalised. As a result, women&#x2019;s participation in decision-making related to reproductive health will improve, as will the health of women and children.</narrative>
  </description>
